<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12033d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12033d">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12033d"> 33(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ bellringer (partner / for adulterers) rings / 13 for 12</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;Parmi ces cloches il y en avait toujours une qui avait une mission sp&eacute;ciale &ldquo; donner adresse aux pauvres gens &eacute;gar&eacute;s dans le brouillard.&raquo; On l&apos;appelait pour cette raison la cloche de brume. Au commencement du XVIIIe si&egrave;cle, elle fut f&ecirc;l&eacute;e. La tradition voulait que, dans certaines circonstances, le seigneur de Foug&egrave;res sonn&acirc;t cette cloche, jusqu&apos;&agrave; ce que le prieur du Mont, &eacute;mu de sa fatigue, lui retir&acirc;t la corde des mains. C&apos;&eacute;tait une sorte de p&eacute;nitence. Un jour, le seigneur du dit lieu, qui avait sur la conscience de gros p&eacute;ch&eacute;s d&apos;infid&eacute;lit&eacute; conjugale, demeura si longtemps cramponn&eacute; &agrave; la corde <font color="green">[216]</font> qu&apos;il agitait fi&eacute;vreusement, que la cloche fut f&ecirc;l&eacute;e. Les religieux furent d&eacute;sol&eacute;s; leurs lamentations parvinrent jusqu&apos;au del&agrave; du Rhin &agrave; leur abb&eacute; commendataire: c&apos;&eacute;tait un Allemand. <br> <font color="green">[Among the bells there is one still today with a special mission, to give guidance to poor people lost in the fog? It is called for that reason the bell of the mists. At the beginning of the eighteenth century, she cracked. Tradition tells us that, in certain circumstances, the lord of Foug&egrave;res sounded the bell, until the prior of the Mont, pitying his tiredness, took the cord from his hands. It was a sort of penitence. One day the lord of that place, who had lots of sins of infidelity weighing on him, clang to the cord that he feverishly rang for such a long time that the bell cracked. The religious thought it was a pity; their laments reached to the other side of the Rhine to the abbot who owned the living; he was a German.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="LMSM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#LMSM"><cite title="source">Les l&eacute;gendes du Mont-Saint-Michel</cite></a> (1924) 216-7</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
